As shown in Tables 1 and 2, the proposed FedTOGA algorithm shows excellent performance on various heterogeneous datasets in terms of convergence speed and final achieved accuracy. Table 1, which details the test accuracy of the LeNet model, demonstrates that FedTOGA significantly outperforms other algorithms with different heterogeneous data conditions. Specifically, under the Dirichlet-0.1 setting on the CIFAR10 dataset, FedTOGA attains an accuracy of 82.05%, marking a significant improvement of over 7.37% compared to vanilla FedAvg and a 1.99% increase over the second-highest baseline accuracy. Similar results are observed in Table 2 for the ResNet18 model, FedTOGA outperforms all current baseline algorithms.

Impact of partial participation.
We fix all hyperparameters except for the client participation rate to assess its effect on accuracy. As illustrated in Table 2, a reduction in the client participation rate from 10% to 5% results in a modest decline in accuracy across all algorithms. For instance, on the CIFAR10 dataset, under the challenging pathological distribution with c=3𝑐3c=3, FedTOGA’s accuracy decreases marginally from 84.55% to 83.35%, a reduction of just 1.40%, while FedSMOO experiences a sharper decline from 82.79% to 81.01%, a reduction of 1.78%. Similarly, under the Dirichlet distribution with u=0.1𝑢0.1u=0.1, FedTOGA’s accuracy decreases from 86.99% to 85.21%, a decrease of 1.78%, whereas FedSMOO’s accuracy drops from 86.08% to 84.96%, a reduction of 1.12%. Notably, despite these reductions, FedTOGA consistently outperforms other algorithms in terms of accuracy, highlighting its robust generalization capability and stability.

To ensure a fair comparison across different datasets, we employed an experimental design consistent with FedGAMMA [7], FedSMOO [41], and FedLESAM [12]. ResNet18 [17] was selected as the backbone model, utilizing group normalization [47] and stochastic gradient descent (SGD). A total of 800 training rounds were conducted, with the initial local learning rate set to ηl=0.1subscript𝜂𝑙0.1\eta_{l}=0.1. The global learning rate was maintained at ηg=1.0subscript𝜂𝑔1.0\eta_{g}=1.0 for most experiments, except for FedAdam and FedYOGI [36] were adjusted to 0.010.010.01. The penalty coefficients α𝛼\alpha for FedDC [16] and FedDyn [2] were uniformly set to 0.010.010.01 in the LeNet, consistent with [16], but were increased to 0.10.10.1 for ResNet18. In FedACG [23], following its prescribed settings, the local penalty coefficient was set to μ=0.01𝜇0.01\mu=0.01, and the server momentum coefficient λ𝜆\lambda was set to 0.850.850.85. For FedAdam and FedYOGI [36], the parameters were set as β1=0.9subscript𝛽10.9\beta_{1}=0.9, β2=0.99subscript𝛽20.99\beta_{2}=0.99, and τ=1​e−3𝜏1superscript𝑒3\tau=1e^{-3}. The momentum trade-off coefficient for FedCM [48] was configured as α=0.1𝛼0.1\alpha=0.1. In the SAM-based algorithms, the penalty coefficients for FedSpeed, FedSMOO, FedLESAM-D, and FedTOGA were uniformly set to α=0.1𝛼0.1\alpha=0.1. The perturbation coefficients for FedGAMMA, FedSpeed, FedSMOO, FedLESAM(S-D), and FedTOGA were consistently set to ρ=0.1𝜌0.1\rho=0.1 for ResNet18, except for FedSAM and MoFedSAM [34] and the vanilla FedLESAM coefficient were set to 0.010.010.01. In the LeNet experiments, the perturbation coefficients ρ𝜌\rho for FedGAMMA, FedLESAM, and its variants were set to 0.010.010.01, though in some cases 0.10.10.1 yielded better performance. Weight decay was uniformly set to 1​e−31superscript𝑒31e^{-3} across all experiments.In the ResNet18 experiments, the learning rate decay were set to 0.9980.9980.998 for most methods, except for FedSMOO, FedLESAM and its variants which were set to 0.99950.99950.9995. In the 200-client case the learning rate decay was set to 0.99950.99950.9995 (This is not always the case, in some cases a learning rate decay of 0.9980.9980.998 works better, and we kept only the best results).
In most scenarios, the local perturbation correction coefficient κ𝜅\kappa for FedTOGA was set to 1; however, in cases of increased heterogeneity, κ𝜅\kappa could be slightly enlarged, but not beyond the local interval value K𝐾K. The local dual variable correction coefficient β𝛽\beta for FedTOGA was chosen within the range of 0 to 1, with 0.80.80.8 or 0.90.90.9 typically performing best on CIFAR10. Generally, the parameter selection range can be determined according to Table 6.

The SAM optimizer usually slows down the whole training process due to the need to compute additional perturbations to the ascent process, which will be improved by enhancing consistency. MoFedSAM enforces consistency by employing global momentum on each local client and weighting it by a factor a (usually 0.1), which means that local knowledge will be forcibly overwritten by global gradient, which, while speeding up convergence in the early stage, may not be able to take any further from the local knowledge in the later stage.
